Twitter suspended more than 10,000 accounts linked to ISIS militants and their supporters in a single 24-hour period .
The social network's so-called 'violations department' suspended about 10,500 accounts used by ISIS militants or supporters of the terror group on April 2 .
Twitter has confirmed that its purge was prompted by the 'large number of reports' received by online activists and members of the public .
It said it will not tolerate accounts tweeting sickening messages promoting violence .